International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 23 Feb 2016
Source: SFGate [edited]
http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Horse-and-dog-killed-with-poisoned-cookies-in-6849887.php


A Sonoma County [California] woman's horse and dog were killed, and another horse she owns was sickened, after the animals ingested cookies laced with poison that apparently were deliberately left for them to eat earlier this month, officials said Tuesday [23 Feb 2016].

Deputies recently identified a person of interest in the poisoning case, but authorities would not give details about the possible suspect, said Sgt. Cecile Focha, a spokeswoman for the Sonoma County Sheriff's Office.

The animals became ill on 12 Feb 2016 after someone planted the homemade cookies laced with oleander toxicity on the woman's property in an unincorporated area of Sebastopol along Kennedy Road.

One of the horses and the dog ultimately died, and necropsies revealed they had been slipped the poisonous plant.

Oleander is an outdoor shrub with delicate flowers found in warm climates. The plant is poisonous to horses, dogs cats, cows and birds and other animals and causes vomiting, seizures, heart failure and often death.

Deputies said the case appears to be an isolated incident and authorities have warned neighbors near where the poisoning occurred.

Anyone with information about the poisoning can call the Sonoma County Sheriff's Office at (707) 565-2185.

[Byline: Evan Sernoffsky]

