[Oleander (_Nerium oleander_) is a beautiful plant with dark green slender leaves and delicate blossoms, generally a bright pink or red, or white. The veins of the leaves are very prominent and can be used for microscopic identification in the stomach contents. All parts of the plant are regarded as toxic. The plant maintains its toxicity even in the dry or dormant state. Branches or leaves that have been cut off and dried or dried because of a frost, are just as toxic as the green leaves.

Oleanders typically grow in warm climates, along the southern coast of the USA, up portions of the western seaboard and the eastern seaboard and many places in the South.

Oleander contains the cardioactive glycosides oleandrin and neriine, and possibly cardenolides and bufodienolides as well. These latter 2 interfere with the electrolyte balance within the heart muscle. Most often the animals die, or those that survive may have permanent cardiac damage. Oleandrin may be another toxin involved. But it takes extremely small bits of any of these toxic principles to produce death.

All parts of the plant are toxic, but these cardioactive glycosides are considered to be highest in the sap. It is extremely toxic and is reported to be bitter. Hungry animals will consume almost anything.

This is a sad and painful way for animals to die. It is even worse to think that a child could have consumed these 'treats' mistakenly.

A photo of oleander may be found at: http://floridata.com/Plants/Apocynaceae/Nerium%20oleander/71. - Mod.TG

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4053960,1018.]
